@pottery.by.doc Here’s a bit of serendipitous fun (gotta use those big words now and then). I made these pieces at different times, some together, but not all together. 
.
No, I didn’t make the shot glass. That’s just there for size perspective.
.
If you swipe across, you’ll see that the bowls fit neatly inside each other, even though I didn’t plan it that way or make them with that in mind.
.
I made all of these because I LOVE this combination of glazes. All of them have Amaco Potters Choice Temmoku glaze on the outside (brushed, 3x). Most of them have Amaco Potters Choice Deep Firebrick on the inside (also brushed 3x). Some of them have Amaco Potters Choice Smokey Merlot on the inside. 
.
.
.
.
.

@pottery.by.doc For my production order. I’m not great at getting them all to be the same (size, shape) or correct (size, shape), but I’m really enjoying the challenge.
.
1. Thrown Friday, trimmed yesterday (Sunday). They had dried too much so the trimming was a challenge and making the holes around the rim was a *big* challenge.
.
2. Thrown Friday, trimmed today. MUCH easier because they weren’t even leather hard yet, so I had to put them outside to dry for a bit.
.
3. Six 4lb balls and one 1lb ball (the remainder of the bag) prepared to throw more.
.
4. Six pots and one bowl (the remainder) thrown today. One of the pots isn’t quite right, so it’ll be mine. ;) 
.
I’m treating this in the manner of an apprenticeship and counting on @nobrainerpottery for guidance. I’m finding that making rounded bottoms has challenges but also eliminates the usual challenge/pleasure of making flat bottoms or foot rings.
.
All pieces made with @armadillo_clay Cinco Rojo. Other than the @mudtools Mudsponges I’m using all generic tools for throwing. Trimming was done with @diamondcoretools trimming tools, one of my favorite Xiem trimming tools, @kempertoolschinoca finishing rubbers.

.
.
.
.

I had the most incredible shoot today. 

@doclistphotography is truly one of the most amazing people and artists I've ever met. 

Not only is he extraordinarily talented at lighting, and photoshop, and everything else behind the lense (and potterymaking, come to think of it!), he's also an engaging and caring and respectful person I feel honoured to know.

Before we worked together, he took some time to get to know us. (If you haven't been paying attention, "us" refers to all four individuals in my brain.) His curiosity was so genuine and respectful, we felt safe to open up to him and share a little of ourselves.

Upon working together, we were surprised to find that we all actually really wanted to shoot with him as individuals, allowing our unique personalities to shine through into the images.
He was not just receptive of the idea, but truly enthusiastic, and made us each feel extremely welcome and honoured. (He even went so far as to provide a stool for Ashe to stand on so he felt the appropriate height for their goodbye hug despite the body being shorter. ...y'all have no idea what that meant to him.)

I am overjoyed to have met such a miraculous and considerate individual...the fact that his art is exquisite is just the sweetest icing on the most delicious cake. 

Every image he's shown me so far is breathtaking but let me whet your appetites with the first of (hopefully) many to come. 💜

There are so many things I love about working with dancers. First is that I get to see them dance. Their self-expression, passion, artistry, humanity, and their ability to connect to the music are moving. 
.
Second is their self-criticism, their sense of perfectionism, and their desire to make it just so… these are inspiring (and frustating) as we do the same sequence or move or pose repeatedly.
.
Finally (all thought not really “final”) is the experience of having them choose their favorite images, which is so revealing about them and their connection to themselves and their art.
.
@ally._.mo dancing for the first time in a few years is an excellent example of all of these. I’m so grateful.
.
